nvironment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H11NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-valine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C10H20N2O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-[(2-amino-3-methylbutanoyl)amino]-3-methylbutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"valylvaline\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formaldehyde-equivalent carbon feedstock\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite\", \"greigite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent-like reducing conditions; included as upstream hydrothermal feedstock connection to surface sugar chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-mediated reduction of CO2 by H2 on iron-bearing hydrothermal surfaces to yield reduced C1 carbon that can feed surface formaldehyde chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature review states that upstream C1 feedstocks such as formaldehyde could arise from hydrothermal chemistry and then feed surface sugar synthesis, providing Hydrothermal -> Surface interconnection. This upstream step is not part of the experimentally demonstrated valine sequence itself, so it is included as a necessary connector and is explicitly more speculative than the surface route. It is consistent with the review's hydrothermal connection discussion and general hydrothermal CO2 reduction chemistry, while the valine-forming sequence itself follows Patel et al. (2015). Citation basis for valine network context: (Patel et al., 2015); connector step acknowledged as speculative per review.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface formose entry to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals\", \"TiO2\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals and TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic/geothermal pool setting; sugar-forming upstream connection to cyanosulfidic precursors\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface carbonyl condensation and stabilization of reduced C1 carbon into a C2 sugar precursor under borate-stabilized photochemically assisted conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The review notes that dihydroxyacetone and hydroxyacetone could arise from formose-type chemistry from formaldehyde in surface settings, though this remains debated. This step is therefore a necessary but upstream connector to the literature-established valine route rather than part of the direct demonstrated sequence. It is included to maintain a connected Hydrothermal -> Surface network and is marked as plausible but less certain than the Patel et al. valine-forming steps. Citation basis for network context: (Patel et al., 2015); upstream formose linkage acknowledged as debated in the review.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface aldol progression to dihydroxyacetone\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals and montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"sugar-generating surface pool chemistry feeding cyanosulfidic valine synthesis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol-type carbon-carbon bond formation among lower carbonyl compounds generates the triose dihydroxyacetone, stabilized by borate-rich surface conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature review identifies dihydroxyacetone as a key starting substrate for the experimentally demonstrated valine pathway and notes that such C3 sugars could derive from formose-type chemistry. This reaction is therefore an upstream connector needed to supply the documented substrate. It is less directly evidenced for the valine-specific system than the downstream cyanosulfidic sequence, but it is consistent with the review's environmental interconnection. Citation basis for valine pathway substrate relevance: (Patel et al., 2015); upstream source remains debated per review.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface isomerizing route to hydroxyacetone\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals\", \"TiO2\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals and TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"surface sugar-derivative generation under geothermal/photochemical conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface-mediated carbonyl rearrangement and reduction chemistry generates hydroxyacetone as an alternative C3 precursor feeding the same acetone hub.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The review identifies hydroxyacetone as the second documented starting substrate for valine synthesis in the Patel et al. network and notes that upstream sugar-derived feedstocks may arise from broader surface or hydrothermal carbonyl chemistry. This reaction is included only to connect the documented substrate into a fully connected network and should be viewed as upstream and less certain than the experimentally demonstrated cyanosulfidic transformations from hydroxyacetone onward. Citation basis: (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Cu/H2S reductive deoxygenation of dihydroxyacetone to acetone\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals\", \"TiO2\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"dissolved Cu0 with H2S under cyanosulfidic conditions represented in surface mineral context\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanosulfidic pool chemistry; reductive deoxygenation; produces acetone plus water\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Copper/H2S-mediated reductive deoxygenation removes the two hydroxyl functionalities of dihydroxyacetone to produce acetone.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is an experimentally documented upstream entry to the acetone hub in the cyanosulfidic valine pathway. The review specifically identifies dihydroxyacetone -> acetone under Cu/H2S conditions as part of the Patel et al. sequence. Because the schema requires mineral agents for all surface reactions but the study uses dissolved copper and H2S, the agents field maps the cyanosulfidic setting onto sulfide-mineral-bearing surface pools while preserving the reported catalytic chemistry in conditions. Supported directly by (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Cu/H2S reductive deoxygenation of hydroxyacetone to acetone\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals\", \"TiO2\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"dissolved Cu0 with H2S under cyanosulfidic conditions represented in surface mineral context\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanosulfidic pool chemistry; alternative upstream entry to acetone\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Copper/H2S-mediated reductive deoxygenation removes the hydroxyl group from hydroxyacetone to yield acetone.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the second experimentally documented route converging on acetone in the Patel et al. valine network. The review explicitly identifies hydroxyacetone -> acetone under Cu/H2S cyanosulfidic conditions. As above, the agents field is adapted to satisfy the required schema while the catalytic details are retained in conditions. Supported directly by (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin formation from acetone and HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface cyanosulfidic conditions\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"nucleophilic cyanide addition to ketone in evaporitic pool chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanide adds to the carbonyl carbon of acetone followed by protonation to form acetone cyanohydrin.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the first nitrile-forming step in the documented valine route. The review directly lists acetone + HCN -> acetone cyanohydrin as Reaction M1 in the Patel et al. sequence. Supported directly by (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Thioamide formation from acetone cyanohydrin\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"H2S-rich cyanosulfidic conditions\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"nitrile activation by sulfur incorporation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrogen sulfide adds across the nitrile functionality to convert the cyanohydrin into the corresponding thioamide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step is explicitly identified in the review as Reaction M2 of the Patel et al. pathway and is essential because the thioamide is the substrate for the key chain-extension rearrangement that builds the valine skeleton. Supported directly by (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Cu/H2S reductive rearrangement and chain extension to 2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals\", \"TiO2\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"dissolved Cu0 with H2S under cyanosulfidic conditions represented in surface mineral context\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"critical C-C bond-forming step; chain extension establishing branched C5 valine skeleton\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Copper/H2S-mediated reductive rearrangement of the thioamide incorporates a second HCN equivalent, forms a new carbon-carbon bond, and yields the branched \u03b1-hydroxynitrile with disulfane byproduct.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The review highlights this as the critical and mechanistically complex C-C bond-forming step that establishes the valine carbon skeleton, with disulfane formed as a byproduct. It is directly reported as Reaction M3 in the Patel et al. network and is the key convergence from early nitrile chemistry to the direct valine precursor branch. Supported directly by (Patel et al., 2015); the review also notes mechanistic open questions for this step.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Amination of 2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile to valine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface aqueous cyanosulfidic amination conditions\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Strecker-type substitution of hydroxyl by amino group\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia substitutes for the alpha-hydroxyl group adjacent to the nitrile to furnish 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is Reaction M4 in the review and is the direct conversion of the branched hydroxynitrile into the immediate aminonitrile precursor of valine. Supported directly by (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis of 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile to L-valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface aqueous hydrolysis conditions\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"final Strecker-type nitrile hydrolysis via amide intermediate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrolysis of the aminonitrile nitrile group yields the corresponding amino acid and releases ammonia.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the principal experimentally documented terminal step to valine, identified as Reaction F1 in the review. The review notes that the broader pathway is expected to generate racemic valine even though the target is written as L-valine. Supported directly by (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Alternative hydrolysis of 2-amino-4-methylpentanenitrile to L-valine with chain shortening\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface aqueous cyanosulfidic hydrolysis conditions\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alternative documented route involving apparent chain shortening during hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrolysis of the C6 aminonitrile produces valine with concomitant loss of one carbon through an unresolved chain-shortening process.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature review explicitly lists this as the second experimentally demonstrated route to valine, designated Reaction F2, while also emphasizing that the mechanism of chain shortening remains unresolved. It is included exactly as reported and flagged as mechanistically open. Supported directly by (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical condensation of valine to valylvaline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n 