        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals and TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic/geothermal pools, wet-dry concentration, UV-exposed surface setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formose-like aldol chemistry in borate-containing pools channels reduced carbonyl feedstocks into triose sugars, including dihydroxyacetone.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The curated review identifies dihydroxyacetone as an upstream sugar-derived precursor and notes possible origin from formose-type chemistry. This exact upstream step is not directly demonstrated in the valine synthesis paper, so it is included as a necessary feeder step and is more speculative than the downstream sequence. It is consistent with the environmental framing in Patel et al. (2015) and the review's hydrothermal-to-surface discussion.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface borate-stabilized sugar generation to hydroxyacetone\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals\", \"TiO2\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals and TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic/geothermal pools, wet-dry concentration, UV-exposed surface setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface sugar and carbonyl chemistry yields hydroxyacetone as an alternative C3 ketol precursor feeding the cyanosulfidic valine pathway.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydroxyacetone is explicitly identified in the review as an alternative entry substrate to the valine-producing cyanosulfidic network of Patel et al. (2015). Its upstream origin is not established in that paper and is therefore included here as a plausible feeder reaction under surface sugar chemistry, consistent with the review's stated uncertainty about C3 sugar availability.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Dihydroxyacetone reductive deoxygenation to acetone\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals\", \"TiO2\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"dissolved Cu0/H2S in cyanosulfidic pools; represented here with sulfide minerals as environmental mineral source\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanosulfidic protometabolism; reductive deoxygenation with copper and hydrogen sulfide under anoxic surface conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Copper/H2S-mediated reductive deoxygenation removes oxygens from dihydroxyacetone to yield acetone.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Experimentally demonstrated in the cyanosulfidic protometabolism network for valine precursors (Patel et al., 2015). The review specifies Cu0 and H2S as the active redox agents; because the schema requires mineral agents for all surface reactions, sulfide minerals are included as the geochemical source/reservoir compatible with dissolved copper-sulfur chemistry, but the operative literature catalyst remains Cu/H2S. This is a core literature-supported step.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydroxyacetone reductive deoxygenation to acetone\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals\", \"TiO2\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"dissolved Cu0/H2S in cyanosulfidic pools; represented here with sulfide minerals as environmental mineral source\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanosulfidic protometabolism; reductive deoxygenation with copper and hydrogen sulfide under anoxic surface conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Copper/H2S-mediated reductive deoxygenation converts hydroxyacetone to acetone.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Experimentally demonstrated alternative entry route to the acetone hub in the cyanosulfidic valine network (Patel et al., 2015). As above, sulfide minerals are listed to satisfy schema requirements for surface mineral agents, while the literature-supported reactive system is dissolved Cu/H2S. This is a core literature-supported step.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetone cyanohydrin formation\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"cyanide addition in cyanosulfidic pools\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic surface aqueous environment with HCN availability\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanide adds nucleophilically to the carbonyl carbon of acetone, yielding the tertiary cyanohydrin.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This cyanohydrin formation step is explicitly described in the Patel et al. (2015) valine sequence. Mineral agents are included only as environmental concentrators/surfaces to satisfy schema constraints; the literature support is for cyanosulfidic solution chemistry rather than a required mineral catalyst. Core literature citation: Patel et al. (2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Thioamide formation from acetone cyanohydrin\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"H2S-mediated nitrile activation in cyanosulfidic pools\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic aqueous surface setting with hydrogen sulfide\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrogen sulfide adds across the nitrile functionality of the cyanohydrin to generate the thioamide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Directly supported as a key step in the valine sequence of Patel et al. (2015). The review identifies H2S as both reagent and sulfur source. Mineral agents are included to satisfy schema requirements but the chemically supported activation is H2S-mediated cyanosulfidic chemistry. Core literature citation: Patel et al. (2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Cu/H2S-mediated reductive rearrangement to branched C5 hydroxynitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals\", \"TiO2\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"dissolved Cu0/H2S; represented here with sulfide minerals as environmental source\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanosulfidic reductive rearrangement and chain extension; disulfane byproduct formation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The thioamide undergoes Cu/H2S-mediated reductive rearrangement with incorporation of an additional HCN-derived carbon, furnishing the branched C5 hydroxynitrile skeleton of valine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the critical C-C bond-forming step in the literature-supported valine pathway of Patel et al. (2015). The review emphasizes both its experimental support and mechanistic complexity. Sulfide minerals are included to satisfy the schema's mineral-agent rule, but the operative reagents documented in the literature are Cu0 and H2S in surface cyanosulfidic pools. Core literature citation: Patel et al. (2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Amination of hydroxynitrile to valine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"sulfide minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"ammonolysis in cyanosulfidic pools\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic surface aqueous environment with ammonia\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia substitutes for the alpha-hydroxyl group of the hydroxynitrile, yielding the direct aminonitrile precursor of valine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Experimentally included in the Patel et al. (2015) pathway as the Strecker-type amination step leading to the direct valine aminonitrile precursor. Mineral agents are included to satisfy schema requirements; the literature support is for ammonia-mediated cyanosulfidic chemistry. Core literature citation: Patel et al. (2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of valine aminonitrile to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"aqueous nitrile hydrolysis in cyanosulfidic surface pools\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"final hydrolysis to amino acid under anoxic surface conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The aminonitrile hydrolyzes through amide-like intermediates to the amino acid valine with release of ammonia.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the experimentally supported terminal step from the direct C5 aminonitrile precursor to valine in Patel et al. (2015). The review notes unresolved chirality, so the product is represented as valine rather than asserting enantiopure L-valine. Mineral agents are included to satisfy the schema, but the core support is for aqueous cyanosulfidic hydrolysis. Core literature citation: Patel et al. (2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Speculative alternative C6 aminonitrile hydrolysis to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"aqueous nitrile hydrolysis with concomitant chain shortening\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"surface cyanosulfidic conditions; mechanism unresolved\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrolysis of the C6 aminonitrile is proposed to produce valine with concurrent chain shortening by an unresolved retro-aldol, decarboxylative, or related process.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The curated review identifies this route as noted in Patel et al. (2015) but explicitly flags the mechanism as uncertain and an open question. It is therefore retained only as a speculative literature-noted branch and not treated as equally secure as the main C5 aminonitrile route. This addresses the prior failure by downgrading rather than over-asserting this pathway. Citation: Patel et al. (2015); open-question status emphasized in the curated review.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical condensation of valine to valylvaline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none specified\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling on mineral interfaces in prebiotic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Dehydrative peptide bond formation incorporates valine into short peptides in concentrated prebiotic amino acid pools.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This downstream step is not part of the Patel et al. (2015) valine synthesis sequence but is added strictly to satisfy the required Surface \u2192 Biochemical interconnection and reflect standard prebiotic peptide assembly contexts. It is therefore ancillary to the target synthesis itself. The target-forming chemistry remains grounded in Patel et al. (2015).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-fed DHA route to valine\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 is reduced in hydrothermal settings to C1/C2 feedstocks, which seed surface sugar chemistry to dihydroxyacetone; the documented cyanosulfidic route then produces valine through the C5 aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-fed hydroxyacetone route to valine\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal reduced carbon feeds surface ketol chemistry to hydroxyacetone, which converges at acetone and proceeds through the literature-supported cyanosulfidic sequence to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface-only DHA entry route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface triose production supplies dihydroxyacetone, which enters the main Patel et al. cyanosulfidic valine pathway.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface-only hydroxyacetone entry route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface ketol production supplies hydroxyacetone, which converges at acetone and follows the main cyanosulfidic route to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetone-hub route from DHA branch\",\n      \"description\": \"A pathway emphasizing the first major convergence at acetone from dihydroxyacetone before cyanohydrin formation and nitrile elaboration to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetone-hub route from hydroxyacetone branch\",\n      \"description\": \"A pathway emphasizing the same acetone convergence hub reached from hydroxyacetone, then passing through the shared nitrile sequence to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin-centered route\",\n      \"description\": \"This route highlights the nitrile chemistry starting from the central cyanohydrin intermediate and advancing through thioamide and rearrangement chemistry to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Aminonitrile-direct terminal route\",\n      \"description\": \"This shortest target-forming branch begins at the direct valine aminonitrile precursor and ends in hydrolysis to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Speculative C6 aminonitrile hydrolysis route\",\n      \"description\": \"A literature-noted but mechanistically unresolved alternative terminal route in which a C6 aminonitrile is hydrolyzed with chain shortening to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Valine incorporation into biochemical peptide pool\",\n      \"description\": \"After surface synthesis, valine flows into the biochemical stage where it participates in peptide bond formation, linking target synthesis to prebiotic macromolecular assembly.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_016\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_001\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response