ive than the core valine chemistry. Iron-mineral-mediated CO2 reduction in hydrothermal settings is broadly supported, while the direct connection to valine precursors is an inferred environmental input consistent with the review's hydrothermal-to-surface feedstock discussion; valine-forming steps themselves follow Patel et al. (2015). Relevant hydrothermal precedent: Huber & Wachtershauser (1997); Preiner et al. (2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal C1 coupling to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite", "mackinawite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic vent-associated carbonyl condensation; feedstock export to surface pools"}, "mechanism": "Reduced C1 carbonyl species undergo mineral-assisted C-C coupling to generate C2 aldehydic sugar precursors.", "reasoning": "Included as an environmental feeder reaction to satisfy Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface interconnection while preserving the literature-supported surface route to valine. The curated review specifically notes that sugar feedstocks could originate from hydrothermal production of formaldehyde followed by aldol chemistry; this step is therefore explicitly speculative but consistent with that stated possibility. Core valine chemistry remains that of Patel et al. (2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Surface borate-stabilized sugar generation to dihydroxyacetone", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals", "TiO2"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals and TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic/geothermal pools, wet-dry concentration, UV-exposed surface setting"}, "mechanism": "Formose-like aldol chemistry in borate-containing pools channels reduced carbonyl feedstocks into triose sugars, in