urface conditions"}, "mechanism": "Copper/H2S-mediated reductive deoxygenation removes oxygens from dihydroxyacetone to yield acetone.", "reasoning": "Experimentally demonstrated in the cyanosulfidic protometabolism network for valine precursors (Patel et al., 2015). The review specifies Cu0 and H2S as the active redox agents; because the schema requires mineral agents for all surface reactions, sulfide minerals are included as the geochemical source/reservoir compatible with dissolved copper-sulfur chemistry, but the operative literature catalyst remains Cu/H2S. This is a core literature-supported step."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Hydroxyacetone reductive deoxygenation to acetone", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_011", "mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals", "TiO2"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "dissolved Cu0/H2S in cyanosulfidic pools; represented here with sulfide minerals as environmental mineral source", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanosulfidic protometabolism; reductive deoxygenation with copper and hydrogen sulfide under anoxic surface conditions"}, "mechanism": "Copper/H2S-mediated reductive deoxygenation converts hydroxyacetone to acetone.", "reasoning": "Experimentally demonstrated alternative entry route to the acetone hub in the cyanosulfidic valine network (Patel et al., 2015). As above, sulfide minerals are listed to satisfy schema requirements for surface mineral agents, while the literature-supported reactive system is dissolved Cu/H2S. This is a core literature-supported step."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Acetone cyanohydrin formation", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "cyanide addition in cyanosulfidic pools", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic surface aqueous environment with HCN availability"}, "mechanism": "Cyanide adds nucleophilically to the carbonyl carbon of acetone, yielding the tertiary cyanohydrin.", "reasoning": "This cyanohydrin formation step is explicitly described in the Patel et al. (2015) valine sequence. Mineral agents are included only as environmental concentrators/surfaces to satisfy schema constraints; the literature support is for cyanosulfidic solution chemistry rather than a required mineral catalyst. Core literature citation: Patel et al. (2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Thioamide formation from acetone cyanohydrin", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "H2S-mediated nitrile activation in cyanosulfidic pools", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic aqueous surface setting with hydrogen sulfide"}, "mechanism": "Hydrogen sulfide adds across the nitrile functionality of the cyanohydrin to generate the thioamide.", "reasoning": "Directly supported as a key step in the valine sequence of Patel et al. (2015). The review identifies H2S as both reagent and sulfur source. Mineral agents are included to satisfy schema requirements but the chemically supported activation is H2S-mediated cyanosulfidic chemistry. Core literature citation: Patel et al. (2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Cu/H2S-mediated reductive rearrangement to branched C5 hydroxynitrile", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_017"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals", "TiO2"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "dissolved Cu0/H2S; represented here with sulfide minerals as environmental source", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanosulfidic reductive rearrangement and chain extension; disulfane byproduct formation"}, "mechanism": "The thioamide undergoes Cu/H2S-mediated reductive rearrangement with incorporation of an additional HCN-derived carbon, furnishing the branched C5 hydroxynitrile skeleton of valine.", "reasoning": "This is the critical C-C bond-forming step in the literature-supported valine pathway of Patel et al. (2015). The review emphasizes both its experimental support and mechanistic complexity. Sulfide minerals are included to satisfy the schema's mineral-agent rule, but the operative reagents documented in the literature are Cu0 and H2S in surface cyanosulfidic pools. Core literature citation: Patel et al. (2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Amination of hydroxynitrile to valine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_015", "mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "sulfide minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "ammonolysis in cyanosulfidic pools", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic surface aqueous environment with ammonia"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia substitutes for the alpha-hydroxyl group of the hydroxynitrile, yielding the direct aminonitrile precursor of valine.", "reasoning": "Experimentally included in the Patel et al. (2015) pathway as the Strecker-type amination step leading to the direct valine aminonitrile precursor. Mineral agents are included to satisfy schema requirements; the literature support is for ammonia-mediated cyanosulfidic chemistry. Core literature citation: Patel et al. (2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Hydrolysis of valine aminonitrile to valine", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "aqueous nitrile hydrolysis in cyanosulfidic surface pools", "aqueous": "true", "other": "final hydrolysis to amino acid under anoxic surface conditions"}, "mechanism": "The aminonitrile hydrolyzes through amide-like intermediates to the amino 