ata indeed names minerals/agents for every surface step. Also, the literature specifically emphasizes dissolved Cu0/H2S rather than classic surface minerals for the core valine sequence, so strict compliance with the earlier generation rubric may be imperfect even though literature alignment is strong. Overall, the network tells a coherent chemical story and does produce valine through experimentally grounded prebiotic chemistry.\",\n  \"approved\": true,\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.90,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.88\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.42, "rxn_002": 0.45, "rxn_003": 0.74, "rxn_005": 0.96, "rxn_007": 0.97, "rxn_008": 0.96, "rxn_009": 0.94, "rxn_010": 0.95, "rxn_011": 0.96}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.79, "pathway_coherence": 0.88, "environmental_progression": 0.9, "target_achievement": 0.97, "overall_confidence": 0.86, "feedback": "Strong overall route to valine with excellent agreement to the Patel et al. cyanosulfidic sequence from dihydroxyacetone onward. The main weakness is the hydrothermal prelude: direct CO2/H2 to formaldehyde and then selective C1 coupling to glycolaldehyde are much less secure than the surface valine sequence and are not the literature-demonstrated route. Once dihydroxyacetone is reached, the chemistry is coherent and target-forming.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002"], "suggestions": ["Downgrade the hydrothermal upstream module to explicitly speculative feedstock generation.", "Include Cu0/H2S explicitly as agents for rxn_005 and cite Patel et al. (2015).", "Clarify that borate-stabilized sugar formation is a feeder pathway rather than part of the experimentally demonstrated valine core sequence."]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.42, "rxn_002": 0.45, "rxn_004": 0.72, "rxn_006": 0.96, "rxn_007": 0.97, "rxn_008": 0.96, "rxn_009": 0.94, "rxn_010": 0.95, "rxn_011": 0.96}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.79, "pathway_