"mol_017"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals", "TiO2"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "dissolved Cu0 and H2S; mineral context represented by sulfide minerals and TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "surface cyanosulfidic conditions; mechanistically complex chain-extension step"}, "mechanism": "Copper/hydrogen sulfide mediated reductive rearrangement of the thioamide with incorporation of an additional HCN-derived carbon to form the branched C5 hydroxynitrile; sulfur oxidation gives disulfane byproduct.", "reasoning": "This is the critical branched-carbon-skeleton-forming step in the experimentally demonstrated valine pathway and is directly supported by Patel et al. (2015). The review emphasizes that the detailed mechanism remains incompletely characterized, so the transformation is well supported experimentally but still mechanistically open."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Amination of branched hydroxynitrile to valine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_015", "mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "surface concentration in cyanosulfidic pool chemistry", "aqueous": "true", "other": "ammonia-rich surface setting"}, "mechanism": "Substitution of the alpha-hydroxyl group by ammonia to produce the direct aminonitrile precursor of valine.", "reasoning": "The review reports this amination as a Strecker-type step converting 2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile to 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile in the Patel et al. (2015) sequence."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Hydrolysis of valine aminonitrile to valine", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_018", "mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "aqueous hydrolysis in concentrated surface pool chemistry", "aqueous": "true", "other": "final nitrile hydrolysis; product expected racemic despite literature naming L-valine"}, "mechanism": "Hydrolysis of the aminonitrile through amide-like intermediacy to the amino acid with release of ammonia.", "reasoning": "This is the principal experimentally supported terminal step to valine in the Patel et al. (2015) network. The supplied review notes unresolved chirality, so although the literature names L-valine, prebiotic product is more plausibly racemic valine."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Alternative C6 aminonitrile hydrolysis to valine", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_018", "mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "aqueous hydrolysis in cyanosulfidic surface pools", "aqueous": "true", "other": "lower-confidence branch; requires chain shortening during or coupled to hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "Hydrolysis of the C6 aminonitrile with coupled chain shortening to yield C5 valine.", "reasoning": "The supplied review explicitly reports this alternative branch as literature-noted but mechanistically unresolved, with chain shortening during hydrolysis remaining an open question (Patel et al., 2015, as summarized in the review). It is therefore retained only as a low-confidence, secondary route and should be considered substantially weaker than the direct C5 aminonitrile hydrolysis path."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Biochemical condensation of valine to valylvaline", "inputs": ["mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral interfaces or wet-dry cycling", "aqueous": "false", "other": "prebiotic pool or mineral interface; dehydration-condensation assembly step"}, "mechanism": "Condensation of valine monomers under drying or interface conditions to a